# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: astronomische-nachrichten
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/1821-in-science] The year **1821 in science** and technology involved some significant events, listed below.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/adalbert-krueger] Krueger died of a heart condition in Kiel at the age of 63.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/adalbert-krueger] In 1851, Krueger entered the University of Berlin where he studied mathematics and science.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/adalbert-krueger] In 1853, showing a special preference for astronomical studies, Krueger moved to the University of Bonn and became an assistant to the astronomer Friedrich Wilhelm Argelander at the Bonn Observatory.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/adalbert-krueger] Under Argelander's supervision he produced data for the comprehensive astrometric star catalogue known as the Bonner Durchmusterung, together with fellow student Eduard Schönfeld .
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/adalbert-krueger] Starting in Bonn, he undertook a lifelong study of the orbit of the minor planet Themis, whose perturbations by Jupiter eventually enabled him in 1873 (while at Helsinki Observatory) to determine the mass of the latter planet.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/adalbert-krueger] He was awarded his doctorate by the University of Bonn in August 1854 for his dissertation titled "*De ascensionibus rectis, a Flamsteedio quadrantis muralis ope observatis*".
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/adalbert-krueger] In 1858 a heliometer previously used by Friedrich Winnecke came into his hands, and was successfully employed in a series of parallax determinations.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/adalbert-krueger] Krueger was made *Privatdozent* in the University in 1860.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/adalbert-krueger] In 1862 Krueger was appointed Professor of Astronomy and Director of the Helsinki Observatory, working there for 14 years.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/adalbert-krueger] At the time of his appointment he married Maria Wilhelmina Amalia, the eldest daughter of Friedrich Argelander.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/adalbert-krueger] While in Helsinki, Krueger carefully determined the position of the stars of the Double Cluster in Perseus.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/adalbert-krueger] The large proper motion of the star Groombridge 34 was first detected by him.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/adalbert-krueger] He also performed observations of variable stars, several comets and minor planets, in addition to his theoretical work.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/adalbert-krueger] After leaving Helsinki, Krueger directed the Gotha Observatory (1876-1880), succeeding the recently deceased Peter Andreas Hansen.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/adalbert-krueger] In Gotha he continued to record data for the Astronomische Gesellschaft Katalog, an astrometric star catalogue.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/adalbert-krueger] Krueger was appointed as Director of the Royal Prussian Observatory in Kiel in 1880.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/adalbert-krueger] In 1881, with the approval of the Astronomical Society (*Astronomische Gesellschaft*), Krueger became the editor of one of the foremost astronomical journals of the day, *Astronomische Nachrichten*; following the death of the former editor Christian Peters the year before.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/adalbert-krueger] Following the death of Krueger in 1896, the editorship passed to his former assistant and son-in-law Heinrich Kreutz.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/akademie-verlag] Under the communist German Democratic Republic, from 1949 to 1990, it remained closely connected to the academy; unlike other publishing houses, it was not subject to direct control by the GDR ministry of culture.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/akademie-verlag] Still, it was regarded with suspicion in the West due to communist influence.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/akademie-verlag] Most of the output was sold in East Germany and the Eastern Bloc.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/akademie-verlag] Since 1957, Gottfried Wilhelm Leibniz, the founder of the Prussian Academy of Sciences in 1700, and „theoria cum praxi“ are used as symbols.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/akademie-verlag] Since the 1970s, several volumes of the Nicolaus Copernicus Gesamtausgabe (complete edition) have been published by Akademie Verlag, covering many documents from and about Nicolaus Copernicus in detail.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/akademie-verlag] *Astronomische Nachrichten* (Astronomical Notes), one of the first international journals in the field of astronomy, founded in 1821, was published by Akademie Verlag for several decades as well as *Physica Status Solidi*, founded in 1961.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/akademie-verlag] After the fall of the Berlin Wall, the employees rejected their boss and elected one of themselves as successor.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/akademie-verlag] As it had managed to build enough of a reputation in the West, several offers were made for Akademie Verlag, and the new German states (including Berlin) sold it on 3 January 1991 to VCH Verlagsgruppe Weinheim.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/akademie-verlag] As a result, of the 170 employees in 1991, only 40 remained until the 50th anniversary in 1996.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/akademie-verlag] The rather broad range of publications was reduced to focus on philosophy, history, political and cultural sciences, history of art, literature, and lingual sciences plus mathematics and physics.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/akademie-verlag] When John Wiley & Sons took over VCH, the natural scientific branch of Akademie Verlag was moved to Wiley-VCH, while the humanities section, including its name and logo, was transferred on 1 October 1997 to R.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/akademie-verlag] Oldenbourg Verlag, which in 2004 was acquired by Cornelsen Verlag.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/akademie-verlag] In 2013, Walter de Gruyter acquired Akademie and Oldenbourg from Cornelsen.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/akademie-verlag] The publisher Walter De Gruyter is digitizing the archive of the Akademie Verlag.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/akademie-verlag] By 2025, this will make more than 15,000 works from the humanities, social sciences, and natural sciences digitally available for the first time.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/altona-observatory] The **Altona Observatory** (German: *Sternwarte Altona*) was an astronomical observatory situated in the Palmaille, in Altona, Hamburg.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/altona-observatory] The observatory was founded by Heinrich Christian Schumacher in 1823 and continued to operate until 1871, 21 years after his death.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/altona-observatory] It closed due to funding being cut off following the cession of the 'Elbe Duchies' of Schleswig, Holstein, and Saxe-Lauenburg by Denmark to Austria and Prussia following the Second Schleswig War.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/altona-observatory] The *Astronomische Nachrichten* journal was founded at the observatory by Schumacher and was edited there until the observatory's closure.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/altona-observatory] In 1815 Heinrich Christian Schumacher initiated a large-scale geodetic survey of Jutland, stretching from Skagen to Lauenburg.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/altona-observatory] To connect the Danish measurements with the greater European geodetic network, Schumacher involved Carl Friedrich Gauss, who in 1818 began his own survey of the Kingdom of Hanover.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/altona-observatory] To connect both networks, a fundamental station was needed in Altona.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/altona-observatory] In 1821 Schumacher acquired a house situated in the Palmaille, in Altona, Hamburg, which was then under Danish administration.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/altona-observatory] In the garden plot behind it, which fell steeply towards the Elbe river and allowed a wide view of the area, he erected the Altona Observatory to house the necessary fundamental station.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/altona-observatory] The royal administration agreed to provide the observatory with an annual budget, under the condition that Schumacher would live and work in Altona until his death.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/altona-observatory] From the windows of the house several survey markers in the south, as well as the tower of St.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/altona-observatory] Michael's Church in the east, could be sighted.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/altona-observatory] A friend of Schumacher's, Johann Georg Repsold, set up a meridian circle in the observatory.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/altona-observatory] In 1823, at the suggestion of the Danish Prime Minister Johan Sigismund von Møsting, Schumacher founded the *Astronomische Nachrichten* journal, one of the first scientific journals in the field of astronomy.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/altona-observatory] Contributions by well-respected astronomers such as Carl Friedrich Gauss, Friedrich Bessel, and William Herschel made the journal, which still publishes to this day, the mouthpiece of the astronomical community.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/altona-observatory] In the 1840s, the Altona-Kiel Railway Company established a 105 km railway line between Altona and the port city of Kiel.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/altona-observatory] It was found, however, that the endpoints of the lines had a time difference in exact astronomical time of about 40 seconds due to their distance.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/altona-observatory] Depending on what time was adopted a train between Altona and Kiel could be considered to have arrived nearly a minute too early or too late, even if it was really on time.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/altona-observatory] To address this problem, the railway, in collaboration with the Altona Observatory and Schumacher, developed an artificial medium time for its timetable, reducing the maximum variation from true geographic time to 20 seconds, which was considerably less noticeable.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/altona-observatory] This issue appeared with all railways as travel distances and speeds increased, eventually leading to the convening of the International Meridian Conference in October 1884 in Washington, D.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/altona-observatory] C., which agreed to adopt a universal day for astronomical purposes, leading to the world being split into time zones independent of precise astronomical time.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/altona-observatory] The observatory continued to make observations throughout the 1840s, with Johann Friedrich Julius Schmidt sighting many astronomical objects in the constellation of Virgo, and Adolph Cornelius Petersen, who later became director, sighting NGC 2194, among others, in 1849.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/altona-observatory] The comet 23P/Brorsen–Metcalf was discovered by Theodor Brorsen at the observatory on 20 July 1847.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/altona-observatory] During the First Schleswig War, the home of Schumacher, who was a royalist Danish official, was surrounded by soldiers and he was placed under house arrest.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/altona-observatory] He died 2 years later, at the end of 1850.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/altona-observatory] Immediately following Schumacher's death, the financial department of Kiel intended to close the observatory.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/altona-observatory] The University of Kiel planned to establish its own observatory and the Hamburg Observatory already existed nearby, making the Altona Observatory redundant.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/altona-observatory] Furthermore, air pollution from factories that were springing up throughout Altona was affecting observations.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/altona-observatory] A lack of funds saw much of the observatory's equipment being sold to the University of Copenhagen and to the University of Kiel, as well as to the navy.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/altona-observatory] Its library went to a Berlin antiquarian, although some works were later repurchased.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/altona-observatory] Schumacher's long-time colleague Adolph Cornelius Petersen was appointed as a temporary director while it was being decided what course of action should be taken.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/altona-observatory] Petersen notably lacked any foreign language skills and struggled to deal with the upkeep of the *Astronomische Nachrichten* journal, which published material from all over Europe.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/altona-observatory] He took language lessons but died shortly after his rise to directorship, in 1854.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/altona-observatory] Finally, a Danish commission decided that the observatory should continue to operate for the time being.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/altona-observatory] In 1854 Christian August Friedrich Peters, who had previous experience working at the Hamburg, Pulkovo, and Königsberg observatories, was appointed as the new director.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/altona-observatory] He continued to publish *Astronomische Nachrichten*, with 58 volumes appearing during his time.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/altona-observatory] Its quality, however, dropped significantly.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/altona-observatory] Peters disliked Russian astronomers and frequently quarrelled with his German counterparts, leading to the journal being shunned by the greater astronomical community.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/altona-observatory] In 1864 the 'Elbe Duchies' of Schleswig, Holstein, and Saxe-Lauenburg were ceded by Denmark to Austria and Prussia following the Second Schleswig War.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/altona-observatory] The new rulers cut off financial support to the observatory and it was decided that it should be abandoned in favour of constructing a new observatory at Kiel.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/altona-observatory] In 1871 construction plans and surveys were completed and Peters moved with his family to Kiel.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/altona-observatory] Work began in the spring of 1874 and, following an unusually hasty construction, was completed by October of the same year.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/altona-observatory] Most of the instruments of the Altona Observatory were transferred to the new building.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/altona-observatory] The home behind which the original observatory was built was destroyed in 1941 during a World War II bombing raid.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/altona-observatory] Today, the German Federal Research Center for Fisheries stands in its place.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/annalen-der-physik] The journal is the successor to *Journal der Physik*, published from 1790 until 1794, and **Neues Journal der Physik**, published from 1795 until 1797.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/annalen-der-physik] The journal has been published under a variety of names (**Annalen der Physik**, **Annalen der Physik und der physikalischen Chemie**, **Annalen der Physik und Chemie**, *Wiedemann's Annalen der Physik und Chemie*) during its history.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/annalen-der-physik] Originally, *Annalen der Physik* was published in German, then a leading scientific language.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/annalen-der-physik] From the 1950s to the 1980s, the journal published in both German and English.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/annalen-der-physik] Initially, only foreign authors contributed articles in English but from the 1970s German-speaking authors increasingly wrote in English in order to reach an international audience.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/annalen-der-physik] After the German reunification in 1990, English became the only language of the journal.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/annalen-der-physik] The importance of *Annalen der Physik* unquestionably peaked in 1905 with Albert Einstein's Annus Mirabilis papers.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/annalen-der-physik] In the 1920s, the journal lost ground to the concurrent *Zeitschrift für Physik*.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/annalen-der-physik] With the 1933 emigration wave, German-language journals lost many of their best authors.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/annalen-der-physik] During Nazi Germany, it was considered to represent "the more conservative elements within the German physics community", alongside *Physikalische Zeitschrift*.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/annalen-der-physik] Between 1944 and 1946 publication ceased due to World War II.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/annalen-der-physik] Granted permission to restart by Soviet military authorities in August 1946, the journal subsequently maintained a policy until 1992 of co-editorship by one person from East Germany and one from West Germany.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/annalen-der-physik] After German reunification, the journal was acquired by Wiley-VCH.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/annalen-der-physik] A relaunch of the journal with new editor and new contents was announced for 2012.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/annalen-der-physik] As a result of the 2012 relaunch, *Annalen der Physik* changed scope and updated the membership of the editorial board.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/annalen-der-physik] With each editor, the numbering of volumes restarted from 1 (co-existent with a continuous numbering, a perpetual source of confusion).
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/annalen-der-physik] The journal was often referred to by the editor's name: *Gilberts Annalen*, *Poggendorfs Annalen*, *Wiedemanns Annalen* and so on, or for short *Pogg.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/annalen-der-physik] After Drude, the work was divided between two editors: experimentalists Wilhelm Wien (1907–1928) and Eduard Grüneisen (1929–1949) and theoretician Max Planck (1907–1943, who had been associate editor from 1895).
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/annalen-der-physik] In these times, peer-review was not yet standard.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/annalen-der-physik] Einstein, for example, just sent his manuscripts to Planck, who then published them.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/annalen-der-physik] According to the *Journal Citation Reports*, the journal has a 2024 impact factor of 2.5.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/astronomical-calculation-institute-heidelberg-university] The **Astronomical Calculation Institute** (German: ***Astronomisches Rechen-Institut***; **ARI**) is a research institute in Heidelberg, Germany, with origins dating back from the 1700s.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/astronomical-calculation-institute-heidelberg-university] Beginning in 2005, the ARI became part of the Center for Astronomy at Heidelberg University (**Zentrum für Astronomie der Universität Heidelberg**, *ZAH*).
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/astronomical-calculation-institute-heidelberg-university] Previously, the institute directly belonged to the state of Baden-Württemberg.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/astronomical-calculation-institute-heidelberg-university] It was founded in 1700 in Berlin-Dahlem by Gottfried Kirch.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/astronomical-calculation-institute-heidelberg-university] It had its origin in a patent application by Frederick I of Prussia, who introduced a monopoly on publishing star catalogs in Prussia.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/astronomical-calculation-institute-heidelberg-university] In 1945 the Institute was moved by the Americans nearer to the United States Army Garrison Heidelberg.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/astronomical-calculation-institute-heidelberg-university] On January 1, 2005 the combined Center for Astronomy institute formed by combining ARI, with the Institute of Theoretical Astrophysics (**Institut für Theoretische Astrophysik**, ITA) and the Landessternwarte Heidelberg-Königstuhl ("Heidelberg-Königstuhl State Observatory", LSW).
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/astronomical-calculation-institute-heidelberg-university] During 1938–1945, whilst based in Berlin, ARI published the academic journal *Astronomical Notes* (German: *Astronomische Nachrichten*).
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/astronomical-calculation-institute-heidelberg-university] As of 2016, ARI was not limited to only publishing star catalogs, but has a wider research scope, including gravitational lensing, galaxy evolution, stellar dynamics, and cosmology.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/astronomical-calculation-institute-heidelberg-university] ARI is also involved in space astronomy missions including the Gaia mission.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/astronomical-calculation-institute-heidelberg-university] Grebel and Joachim Wambsganß became co-directors of the institute.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/astronomical-calculation-institute-heidelberg-university] Other researchers involved with the institute include Hartmut Jahreiß author of the updated *Gliese Catalogue of Nearby Stars*; Eugene Rabe; Lutz D.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/astronomical-calculation-institute-heidelberg-university] Schmadel, author of the *Dictionary of Minor Planet Names*; Hans Scholl; and Rainer Spurzem working with N-body simulations.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/astronomical-calculation-institute-heidelberg-university] Between 1700 and 2007 there was a single director of the institute at a time.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/astronomical-journal] Until 2008, the journal was published by the University of Chicago Press on behalf of the AAS.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/astronomical-journal] The reasons for the change to the IOP were given by the society as the desire of the University of Chicago Press to revise its financial arrangement and their plans to change from the particular software that had been developed in-house.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/astronomical-journal] The other two publications of the society, the *Astrophysical Journal* and its supplement series, followed in January 2009.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/astronomical-journal] The journal was established in 1849 by Benjamin A.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/astronomical-journal] It ceased publication in 1861 due to the American Civil War, but resumed in 1885.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/astronomical-journal] Between 1909 and 1941 the journal was edited in Albany, New York.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/astronomical-journal] In 1941, editor Benjamin Boss arranged to transfer responsibility for the journal to the AAS.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/astronomical-journal] The first electronic edition of *The Astronomical Journal* was published in January, 1998.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/astronomical-journal] With the July, 2006 issue, *The Astronomical Journal* began *e-first* publication, an electronic version of the journal released independently of the hardcopy issues.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/astronomical-journal] As of 2016, all of the scientific AAS journals were placed under a single editor-in-chief.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/astronomical-journal] On January 1, 2022, the AAS Journals, including AJ, transitioned to Gold open access model, with all new papers released under a Creative Commons Attribution license and access restrictions and subscription charges removed from previously published papers.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/astronomische-nachrichten] The journal was founded in 1821 by Heinrich Christian Schumacher, under the patronage of Christian VIII of Denmark, and quickly became the world's leading professional publication for the field of astronomy.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/astronomische-nachrichten] Schumacher edited the journal at the Altona Observatory, then under the administration of Denmark, later part of Prussia, and today part of the German city of Hamburg.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/astronomische-nachrichten] Schumacher edited the first 31 issues of the journal, from its founding in 1821 until his death in 1850.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/astronomische-nachrichten] These early issues ran to hundreds of pages, and consisted mostly of letters sent by astronomers to Schumacher, reporting their observations.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/astronomische-nachrichten] The journal proved to be a great success, and over the years Schumacher received thousands of letters from hundreds of contributors.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/astronomische-nachrichten] The letters were published in the language in which they were submitted, mostly German, but also English, Italian and other languages.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/astronomische-nachrichten] Other astronomical journals were also founded around this time, such as the British *Monthly Notices of the Royal Astronomical Society*, which was founded in 1827.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/astronomische-nachrichten] It was the importance of *Astronomische Nachrichten*, however, that led the American astronomer Benjamin A.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/astronomische-nachrichten] Gould in 1850 to found *The Astronomical Journal* in the United States.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/astronomische-nachrichten] Following Schumacher's death, the interim director of the observatory and editor of the journal was Adolph Cornelius Petersen, who had worked at the observatory with Schumacher for 24 years from around 1825.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/astronomische-nachrichten] Petersen, who died in 1854, was later aided as editor by the Danish astronomer Thomas Clausen, who had also previously worked at the observatory.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/astronomische-nachrichten] The editor from 1854 was the German astronomer Christian August Friedrich Peters, who had taken over as director of the observatory at Altona.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/astronomische-nachrichten] In 1872, the observatory moved from Altona to Kiel, from where Peters continued to publish the journal until his death in 1880, aided in his final years by his son Carl Friedrich Wilhelm Peters.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/astronomische-nachrichten] The journal would continue to be published in Kiel until 1938.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/astronomische-nachrichten] Following Peters's death, Adalbert Krueger served as the new director of the observatory and editor of the journal from 1881 until he died in 1896.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/astronomische-nachrichten] At this time the journal was the organ of the Astronomische Gesellschaft.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/astronomische-nachrichten] The editor from 1896 until his death in 1907 was the German astronomer Heinrich Kreutz, who had previously assisted Krueger.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/astronomische-nachrichten] Other staff members during the period from 1880 to 1907 included the astronomers Richard Schorr and Elis Strömgren.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/astronomische-nachrichten] In 1892, *Astronomische Nachrichten* began assigning provisional designations of minor planets upon receipt of the notice of discovery.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/astronomische-nachrichten] A permanent minor-planet designation was assigned after an orbit had been reliably determined.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/astronomische-nachrichten] This responsibility was later assumed by the International Astronomical Union.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/astronomische-nachrichten] The editor from 1907 to 1938 was the German astronomer Hermann Kobold.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/astronomische-nachrichten] After Kobold retired in 1938, the journal's editorial office moved from Kiel to Berlin, and during the Second World War the journal was published by the Astronomical Calculation Institute (Heidelberg University) (Astronomisches Recheninstitut) in Berlin-Dahlem.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/astronomische-nachrichten] In 1945, the institute was relocated to Heidelberg, but the journal remained in the Berlin region.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/astronomische-nachrichten] After the war, *Astronomische Nachrichten* was edited by Hans Kienle, director of the Astrophysical Observatory of Potsdam.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/astronomische-nachrichten] The observatory was in Potsdam, on the outskirts of Berlin, and from 1948 the journal was published by the publishing company Akademie-Verlag, under the auspices of the German Academy of Sciences Berlin.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/astronomische-nachrichten] One of Kienle's students, Johann Wempe (1906–1980) succeeded him as editor in 1951 and held the post for 22 years.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/astronomische-nachrichten] From 1949, and officially from the 1950s until the reunification of Germany in 1990, the journal was published in the German Democratic Republic, behind the Iron Curtain.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/astronomische-nachrichten] From 1974 onwards, the journal issues list a chief editor and an editorial board, and the journal was bilingual, with the same material published in German and English.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/astronomische-nachrichten] Akademie-Verlag was taken over by VCH in 1990.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/astronomische-nachrichten] From 1996 to the present day (from volume 317), the journal has been published by Wiley-VCH.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/astronomische-nachrichten] This company was formed in 1996 when the German publishing company Verlag Chemie (founded 1921) joined John Wiley and Sons.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/astronomische-nachrichten] The journal's editorial offices remain in Potsdam, at the Astrophysical Institute Potsdam, and the current editor (2007) is K.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/astronomische-nachrichten] The back catalogue of the journal includes 43,899 articles in 99,565 pages in 328 volumes, published over a period of over 180 years.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/astronomische-nachrichten] Although the journal was founded in 1821, the first volume was dated 1823.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/astronomische-nachrichten] Volume 1 (1823) consisted of 33 issues and a total of 516 pages.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/astronomische-nachrichten] The next year, volume 2 (1824), saw 34 issues and 497 pages.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/astronomische-nachrichten] Apart from the years 1830–1832, when two volumes were published in 1831 and none in 1830 or 1832, single volumes of around 20–30 issues were published each year until 1846.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/astronomische-nachrichten] Then it was mostly two volumes a year until 1884.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/astronomische-nachrichten] There were a record number of five volumes published in 1884.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/astronomische-nachrichten] Most years from 1884 to 1914 had three or more volumes.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/astronomische-nachrichten] The years 1915–1919 (coinciding with World War I) saw a dip in publication, with 1916 and 1919 only featuring one volume.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/astronomische-nachrichten] From 1920 to 1940, most years saw three volumes published.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/astronomische-nachrichten] Only one volume per year was published from 1941 to 1943, and the journal was not published at all from 1944 to 1946 (Berlin suffered heavy damage in the closing years of World War II).
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/astronomische-nachrichten] From 1947 to the present, the journal has published a volume per year in most years, but did not publish at all in some years in the 1950s, 1960s and 1970s.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/astronomische-nachrichten] From 1974 to 1996, the journal was published as 6 issues a year, with each volume being 300–400 pages.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/astronomische-nachrichten] Under the new publishers, Wiley, this pattern continued until 2003, at which point the number of issues per year increased to 9 due to the publication of supplementary issues.
[src:astronomische-nachrichten/astronomische-nachrichten] Since 2004 there have been 10 issues a year.
